{"summary":"The text discusses the power and might of the Lord in battle, specifically how He uses different groups, such as the Roman army, to defeat His adversaries, including the Jewish people. It highlights the internal strife among the Jews and the external siege by the Romans as instruments used by God to fulfill His purposes. The Jews' choice to prefer Barabbas over Christ is seen as part of this divine battle, leading to the Romans taking control of their land and nation. The Lord is portrayed as strong and capable in this spiritual and physical conflict.","keywords":["Anti-Judaism","Warfare / Militant imagery","Vengeance"]}